SIMPLE: fob
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Fob
<hw>Fob</hw> <pr>(f⟦ocr⟧b)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. Prov. G.
<ets>fuppe</ets> pocket.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A little pocket for a
watch; -- callled also a <altname>watch pocket</altname>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>a short chain or ribbon attached to a pocket watch,
usually worn hanging out of the watch pocket, and used to conveniently
remove the watch from the watch pocket.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Fob chain</b></col>, <cd>a short watch chain worn with a
watch carried in the fob; a fob{2}.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Fob</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Fob
<hw>Fob</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Fobbed</conjf> <pr>(#)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Fobbing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Cf.Fop.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To beat; to maul.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To cheat; to trick; to impose on.</def>
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To fob off</b></col>, <cd>to shift off by an artifice; to
put aside; to delude with a trick."A conspiracy of bishops could
prostrate and fob off the right of the people."</cd>
<rj><au>Milton.</au></rj></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Focal</ent>⟦br⟧
